314	David Livingstone	David Livingstone (19 March 1813 – 1 May 1873) was a Scottish Congregationalist pioneer medical missionary with the London Missionary Society and an explorer in Africa. His meeting with H. M. Stanley on 10 November 1871 gave rise to the popular quotation "Dr. Livingstone, I presume?" Perhaps one of the most popular national heroes of the late 19th century in Victorian Britain, Livingstone had a mythic status, which operated on a number of interconnected levels: Protestant missionary martyr, working-class "rags to riches" inspirational story, scientific investigator and explorer, imperial reformer, anti-slavery crusader, and advocate of commercial empire. His fame as an explorer helped drive forward the obsession with discovering the sources of the River Nile that formed the culmination of the classic period of European geographical discovery and colonial penetration of the African continent.[citation needed]\nAt the same time his missionary travels, "disappearance" and death in Africa, and subsequent glorification as posthumous national hero in 1874 led to the founding of several major central African Christian missionary initiatives carried forward in the era of the European "Scramble for Africa".	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/ff/Map_livingstone_travels_africa.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Livingstone	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/ff/Map_livingstone_travels_africa.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4c/Wikisource-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/85/Livingstone_statue2.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/69/The_Slave_Gang_%28relates_to_David_Livingstone%29_by_The_London_Missionary_Society.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fc/Padlock-silver.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f2/David_Livingstone_statue%2C_Glasgow.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c8/David_Livingstone_memorial_at_Victoria_Falls%2C_Zimbabwe.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/89/Livingstone_03.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/30/David_Livingstone_statue%2C_Princes_Street_Gardens%2C_Edinburgh.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Birthplace_of_david_livingstone.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9e/MaryMoffatGravestone.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cc/David_Livingstone_by_Frederick_Havill.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d5/David_Livingstone.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e7/Stanley_-_Comment%E2%80%A6_11.png", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/59/Livingstone_Memorial%2C_Tanzania.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a6/Livingstone_House%2C_Mikindani%2C_Tanzania.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ef/Preaching_from_a_Waggon_%28David_Livingstone%29_by_The_London_Missionary_Society.jpg"]	f	cover
213	Jean-Antoine Watteau	Jean-Antoine Watteau (French: [ʒan‿ɑ̃twan wato]; baptised October 10, 1684 – July 18, 1721) better known as Antoine Watteau was a French painter whose brief career spurred the revival of interest in colour and movement (in the tradition of Correggio and Rubens). He revitalized the waning Baroque style, and indeed moved it to the less severe, more naturalistic, less formally classical Rococo.\nWatteau is credited with inventing the genre of fêtes galantes: scenes of bucolic and idyllic charm, suffused with an air of theatricality. Some of his best known subjects were drawn from the world of Italian comedy and ballet.	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Antoine_Watteau	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9c/Jean-Antoine_Watteau_-_Mezzetin.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f5/WatteauPierrot.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/73/Watteau%2C_Antoine_-_Quellnymphe_-_1708.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/94/Gersaint.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8e/WatteauLes_Fetesvenitiennes.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/40/Jean-Antoine_Watteau_La_Surprise%2C_oil_on_panel.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/ab/Antoine_Watteau_-_The_Love_Lesson_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4b/Antoine_Watteau_-_The_Festival_of_Love_-_WGA25460.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a2/Antoine_Watteau_012.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4c/Antoine_Watteau_001.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7f/Antoine_Watteau_-_L%27imbarco_per_Citera.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5a/Jean-Antoine_Watteau_-_The_Love_Song.JPG", "http://upload.wik