76	Rough Wooing	The Rough Wooing (December 1543 – March 1550) was a conflict between Scotland and England. War was declared by Henry VIII of England, in an attempt to force the Scots to agree to a marriage between his son Edward and the infant Mary, Queen of Scots. Scotland benefited from French military aid, under the Auld Alliance. Edward VI continued the war until changing circumstances made it irrelevant in 1550. It was the last major conflict between Scotland and England before the Union of the Crowns in 1603, excepting perhaps the English intervention at the Siege of Leith in 1560, and was part of the Anglo-Scottish Wars of the 16th century.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/02/Mary_Stuart_Young6.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rough_Wooing	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9c/Hans_Eworth_Sir_John_Luttrell.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/ff/Facsimile_of_the_Hertford_sketch_of_1544.tiff", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f6/Moubray_House_and_John_Knox%27s_House%2C_High_Street_Edinburgh.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/02/Mary_Stuart_Young6.jpg"]	f	60%
77	John Knox	John Knox (c. 1514 – 24 November 1572) was a Scottish clergyman and a leader of the Protestant Reformation who is considered the founder of the Presbyterian denomination in Scotland. He is believed to have been educated at the University of St Andrews and worked as a notary-priest. Influenced by early church reformers such as George Wishart, he joined the movement to reform the Scottish church. He was caught up in the ecclesiastical and political events that involved the murder of Cardinal Beaton in 1546 and the intervention of the regent of Scotland Mary of Guise. He was taken prisoner by French forces the following year and exiled to England on his release in 1549.\nWhile in exile, Knox was licensed to work in the Church of England, where he rose in the ranks to serve King Edward VI of England as a royal chaplain. He exerted a reforming influence on the text of the Book of Common Prayer. In England he met and married his first wife Margery Bowes. When Mary Tudor ascended the throne and re-established Roman Catholicism, Knox was forced to resign his position and leave the country. Knox moved to Geneva and then to Frankfurt. In Geneva he met John Calvin, from whom he gained experience and knowledge of Reformed theology and Presbyterian polity. He created a new order of service, which was eventually adopted by the reformed church in Scotland. He left Geneva to head the English refugee church in Frankfurt but he was forced to leave over differences concerning the liturgy, thus ending his association with the Church of England.\nOn his return to Scotland he led the Protestant Reformation in Scotland, in partnership with the Scottish Protestant nobility. The movement may be seen as a revolution, since it led to the ousting of Mary of Guise, who governed the country in the name of her young daughter Mary, Queen of Scots. Knox helped write the new confession of faith and the ecclesiastical order for the newly created reformed church, the Kirk. He continued to serve as the religious leader of the Protestants throughout Mary's reign. In several interviews with the Queen, Knox admonished her for supporting Catholic practices. When she was imprisoned for her alleged role in the murder of her husband Lord Darnley, and King James VI enthroned in her stead, he openly called for her execution. He continued to preach until his final days.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0b/Knox_Dispensing_the_Sacrament_at_Calder_House.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Knox	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/89/KnoxMaryLongBeachCovenantPC.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fa/Wikiquote-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/21/KnoxDetailRefWall.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4c/Wikisource-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/66/St_John%27s_Kirk%2C_Perth.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/e/e7/Cscr-featured.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0b/Knox_Dispensing_the_Sacrament_at_Calder_House.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e4/John_Knox%27s_House%2C_High_Street%2C_Edinburgh.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/de/Grave_of_John_Knox%2C_Parliament_Square%2C_Edinburgh.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/76/John_Knox_statue%2C_Haddington.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/31/John_Knox_Church_in_Brighton.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8b/Calvin.png", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/28/KnoxRefWall.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Firstblast.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/57/Calvin_Auditory.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2f/St._Giles%27_Cathedral_front.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/2e/Knoxbezaicones.jpg"