289	Richard Arkwright	Sir Richard Arkwright (23 December 1732 – 3 August 1792) was a self-made man and a leading entrepreneur during the early Industrial Revolution. Although the patents were eventually overturned, he is credited with inventing the spinning frame, which, following the transition to water power was renamed the water frame. He also patented a rotary carding engine that transformed raw cotton into cotton lap.\nArkwright's achievement was to combine power, machinery, semi-skilled labour and the new raw material (cotton) to create mass-produced yarn. His skills of organisation made him, more than anyone else, the creator of the modern factory system, especially in his mill at Cromford. Later in his life Arkwright was known as 'the Father of the Industrial Revolution'.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cd/Sir_Richard_Arkwright_by_Mather_Brown_1790.jpeg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Arkwright	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4c/Wikisource-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/cd/Sir_Richard_Arkwright_by_Mather_Brown_1790.jpeg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ea/Arkright%27s_Mill_-_Cromford_29-04-06.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ea/Arkwright_Richard_1790.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a0/Arkwright-water-frame.jpg"]	f	50%
372	Henri Matisse	Henri-Émile-Benoît Matisse (French: [ɑ̃ʁi matis]; 31 December 1869 – 3 November 1954) was a French artist, known for his use of colour and his fluid and original draughtsmanship. He was a draughtsman, printmaker, and sculptor, but is known primarily as a painter. Matisse is commonly regarded, along with Pablo Picasso and Marcel Duchamp, as one of the three artists who helped to define the revolutionary developments in the plastic arts in the opening decades of the twentieth century, responsible for significant developments in painting and sculpture. Although he was initially labelled a Fauve (wild beast), by the 1920s he was increasingly hailed as an upholder of the classical tradition in French painting. His mastery of the expressive language of colour and drawing, displayed in a body of work spanning over a half-century, won him recognition as a leading figure in modern art.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/8f/Henri_Matisse_Self-Portrait_in_a_Striped_T-shirt_%281906%29.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Matisse	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/c/ce/Henri_Matisse%2C_1907%2C_La_coiffure%2C_116_x_89_cm%2C_oil_on_canvas%2C_Staatsgalerie%2C_Stuttgart.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/a/ac/Henri_Matisse%2C_1904%2C_Nu_%28Carmelita%29%2C_oil_on_canvas%2C_81.3_x_59_cm%2C_Museum_of_Fine_Arts%2C_Boston.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4f/Matisse518.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f9/Yellow_Curtain.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/2f/Matisse_-_Vase_of_Sunflowers_%281898%29.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/c/c7/Henri_Matisse%2C_Le_Luxe_II%2C_1907%E2%80%938%2C_Distemper_on_canvas%3B_82_1-2_x_54_3-4_in._%28209.5_x_138_cm%29%2C_Statens_Museum_for_Kunst%2C_Copenhagen.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/22/Matisse_-_Fruit_and_Coffeepot_%281898%29.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/0a/Matisse-The-Dessert-Har