436	Warsaw Pact	The Warsaw Pact (formally, the Treaty of Friendship, Co-operation, and Mutual Assistance) was a mutual defense treaty among eight communist States of Central and Eastern Europe in existence during the Cold War. The founding treaty was established under the initiative of the Soviet Union and signed on 14 May 1955, in Warsaw. The Warsaw Pact was the military complement to the Council for Mutual Economic Assistance (CoMEcon), the regional economic organization for the communist States of Central and Eastern Europe. The Warsaw Pact was in part a Soviet military reaction to the integration of West Germany into NATO in 1955, per the Paris Pacts of 1954 but was primarily motivated by Soviet desires to maintain control over military forces in Central and Eastern Europe which in turn (according to The Warsaw Pact's preamble) to maintain peace in Europe, guided by the objective points and principles of the Charter of the United Nations (1945) after the collapse of the USSR and the end of the Cold War. The alliance was transformed into the subsequent Collective Security Treaty Organization, or CSTO.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a9/Flag_of_the_Soviet_Union.svg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warsaw_Pact	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b6/Warsaw-stamp.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4b/%D0%97%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%BA_%D0%92%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%88%D0%B0%D0%B2%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE_%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B2%D1%80%D0%B0_%D0%AE%D0%93.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/23/%D0%97%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%87%D0%BE%D0%BA_%D0%92%D0%92%D0%A1_%D0%92%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%88%D0%B0%D0%B2%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE_%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%B0.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/62/Wappen_Habsburg-Lothringen_Schild.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/17/%D0%97%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%BA_%D0%92%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%88%D0%B0%D0%B2%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%BE