483	Neoclassicism	Neoclassicism (from Greek νέος nèos and κλασσικός klassikòs classicus) is the name given to Western movements in the decorative and visual arts, literature, theatre, music, and architecture that draw inspiration from the "classical" art and culture of Ancient Greece or Ancient Rome. The main Neoclassical movement coincided with the 18th century Age of Enlightenment, and continued into the early 19th century, latterly competing with Romanticism. In architecture, the style continued throughout the 19th and 20th centuries and into the 21st.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d3/Psyche_revived_Louvre_MR1777.jpg/602px-Psyche_revived_Louvre_MR1777.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neoclassicism	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/99/Question_book-new.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3e/Table_Empire.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f5/Th%C3%A9r%C3%A9sa_Cabarrus.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d3/Psyche_revived_Louvre_MR1777.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b6/Schadow_Herkules_und_die_Rosse_des_Diomedes_2.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/05/Schermerhorn.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c9/Sergelfaun.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c9/Museo_delle_porcellane_di_Firenze%2C_servizio_di_elisa_baciocchi%2C_sevres%2C_1809-1810_03.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/28/Nydia-3%2C_Randolph_Rogers.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/51/Ostdv5.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5f/Portrait_de_madame_de_Verninac_by_David_Louvre_RF1942-16_n2.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/31/Discobole_lan%C3%A7ant_le_disque-ChatsworthHouse.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bb/David-Oath_of_the_Horatii-1784.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4e/FuseliArtistMove