239	Marie Antoinette	Marie Antoinette (/məˈriː æntwəˈnɛt/ or /æntwɑːˈnɛt/; French: [maʁi ɑ̃twanɛt]; baptised Maria Antonia Josepha (or Josephina) Johanna; 2 November 1755 – 16 October 1793), born an Archduchess of Austria, was Dauphine of France from 1770 to 1774 and Queen of France and Navarre from 1774 to 1792. She was the fifteenth and penultimate child of Holy Roman Empress Maria Theresa and Emperor Francis I.\nIn April 1770, upon her marriage to Louis-Auguste, Dauphin of France, she became Dauphine of France. She assumed the title Queen of France and of Navarre when her husband ascended the throne as Louis XVI upon the death of his grandfather Louis XV in May 1774. After seven years of marriage, she gave birth to a daughter, Marie-Thérèse Charlotte, the first of four children.\nInitially charmed by her personality and beauty, the French people eventually came to dislike her, accusing "L'Autrichienne" (which literally means the Austrian (woman), but also suggests the French word "chienne", meaning bitch) of being profligate, promiscuous, and of harbouring sympathies for France's enemies, particularly Austria, her country of origin. The Diamond Necklace incident damaged her reputation further, although she was completely innocent in this affair. She later became known as Madame Déficit because France's financial crisis was blamed on her lavish spending.\nThe royal family's flight to Varennes had disastrous effects on French popular opinion: Louis XVI was deposed and the monarchy abolished on 21 September 1792; the royal family was subsequently imprisoned at the Temple Prison. Eight months after her husband's execution, Marie Antoinette was herself tried, convicted by the Revolutionary Tribunal of treason to the principles of the revolution, and executed by guillotine on 16 October 1793.\nLong after her death, Marie Antoinette is often considered to be a part of popular culture and a major historical figure, being the subject of several books, films and other forms of media. Some academics and scholars have deemed her frivolous and superficial, and have attributed the start of the French Revolution to her; however, others have claimed that she was treated unjustly and that views of her should be more sympathetic.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/20/Alexander_Kucharski%2C_La_Reine_Marie-Antoinette_%28ann%C3%A9es_1790%29.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marie_Antoinette	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/eb/Queen%27s_garden_and_Hamlet_Versailles.JPG", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/30/Royal_Monogram_of_Queen_Marie-Antoinette_of_France.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7d/Marie_Antoinette_by_Joseph_Ducreux.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f0/Marie_Antoinette_in_Muslin_dress.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b2/Marie_Antoinette_%C3%A0_la_paysan.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5a/Prinsenvlag.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/87/Marie_Antoinette_1767.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4f/Marie_Antoinette_Adult.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/72/Marie_Antoinette_Adult7.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b6/Marie_Antoinette_Young4.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fd/Lebr04.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/83/Jacques-Louis_David_-_Marie_Antoinette_on_the_Way_to_the_Guillotine.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/fe/Louis_XVI_et_Marie-Antoinette.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/90/Louis_Auguste_Dauphin.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/dc/Marie-AntoinetteSignature.png", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/02/Marie-Antoinette%3B_koningin_der_Fransen.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/68/Marie-Antoinette_par_Elisabeth_Vig%C3%A9e-Lebrun_-_1783.jpg", "http://uplo