254	Jean-Paul Marat	Jean-Paul Marat (French: [ʒɑ̃pɔl maʁa]; 24 May 1743 – 13 July 1793), born in the Principality of Neuchâtel, was a physician, political theorist and scientist best known for his career in France as a radical journalist and politician during the French Revolution. His journalism became renowned for its fierce tone, uncompromising stance toward the new leaders and institutions of the revolution, and advocacy of basic human rights for the poorest members of society.\nMarat was one of the most radical voices of the French Revolution. He became a vigorous defender of the sans-culottes, publishing his views in pamphlets, placards and newspapers, notably his "L'Ami du peuple", which helped make him their unofficial link with the radical, republican Jacobin group that came to power after June 1793.\nMarat was assassinated by Charlotte Corday, a Girondist sympathizer, while taking a medicinal bath for his debilitating skin condition. In his death Marat became an icon to the Jacobins, a sort of revolutionary martyr, as portrayed in David's famous painting of his death.	\N	\N	\N	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/80/Jean-Paul_Marat_portre.jpg	\N	Wikipedia.org	http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Paul_Marat	["http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f3/Flag_of_Russia.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/62/PD-icon.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/c/c3/Flag_of_France.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/33/Triomphe_de_Marat4.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/80/Jean-Paul_Marat_portre.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/45/Jacques-Louis_David_-_La_Mort_de_Marat.jpg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg", "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5a/Prinsenvlag.svg", "http://